##Unexpected outbreak catalyzes change in retail consumption

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

While the epidemic has had a negative impact on the economy, it has also accelerated the escalation of related industries. The outbreak or into the retail industry evolution and change the "catalyst" to accelerate the rise of new retail models

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fruit and vegetable shops on a street in Wuchang District, Wuhan, on February 14,2010. Photo by Wang Xiao, CAIJING reporter

By Zhou Jingtong and Ye Yindan

The new outbreak of pneumonia, which began at the end of December 2019, will have a major short-term impact on the Chinese economy. As the outbreak coincides with the Spring Festival consumption season, compared to investment and exports, the outbreak will have a greater impact on short-term consumption.

However, the impact of the epidemic on consumption "danger" and "opportunity" coexist. In the short term, the epidemic will have a structural impact on consumption of all kinds, and the growth rate of consumption will decrease obviously.

In the medium and long term, the outbreak will promote the change of Chinese residents'consumption behavior and stimulate new consumption growth points, and accelerate the arrival of new retail waves such as unmanned retail and fresh e-commerce.

We suggest that, in the short term, the banking industry should respond quickly to serve the overall situation of national prevention and control of the epidemic and the restoration of economic and social order, and strengthen its support to small and medium-sized enterprises, especially those in the consumer sector, and epidemic prevention-related enterprises and personnel to support the financial support; in the medium and long term, seize the epidemic crisis may be brewing consumer retail industry changes, layout in advance.

The impact of the epidemic on consumption is far greater than SARS

The outbreak occurred in the peak consumption season, and the epidemic spread over a larger area with stronger prevention and control measures. From the point of view of the impact time, the current outbreak of COVID-19 is mainly concentrated in the first quarter of 2020, which coincides with the Spring Festival, Lantern Festival and other traditional consumption season, so the impact on consumption is relatively large; while the outbreak time of SARS in 2003 was in the spring, the impact on consumption is relatively small. In terms of the number of people infected and the extent of the epidemic, the number of people affected by the epidemic far exceeded SARS, with 59,741 confirmed cases in the country as of February 12,2020, while the number of confirmed cases in the country as of August 16,2003 was only 5,327. In addition, the spread of the epidemic is also larger than SARS. SARS mainly broke out in Guangdong Province and Beijing city, which had less impact on production, business and daily life in other parts of the country. This outbreak is not only particularly serious in Hubei Province, where the outbreak occurred, most parts of the country have been hit hard (Tibet, Xinjiang, Qinghai, Gansu, Inner Mongolia and other places are relatively lightly) .

From the point of view of prevention and control measures, during the SARS period, only the epidemic center of Guangdong Province and Beijing City took more strict prevention and control measures, and other areas of production and management, teaching, life and other activities were not affected in a large scale. The current outbreak coincides with the Spring Festival population flow period, in order to prevent the outbreak of Spring Festival caused by the superposition of out of control, all places have taken road closures, closed shops and factories, delayed the opening of construction, closed management of small areas and other very strong prevention and control measures. These tough measures in a strong way to block the spread of the virus, but also a huge blow to consumption.

At present, the proportion of service consumption and optional consumption which are more affected by the epidemic is higher in China's consumption structure.

Compared with the SARS period in 2003, the current income level of Chinese residents has increased significantly and Engel's coefficient has decreased significantly. The disposable income rose from 8,472 yuan in 2003 to 42,359 yuan in 2019. The Engel's Coefficient of urban households (food as a proportion of total household consumption expenditure) and rural households Engel's coefficient 28% and 30% respectively in 2019, down from 37% and 46% in 2003.

The consumption structure of the country's residents has been significantly upgraded, and the proportion of consumption in the service category and the optional category has increased significantly. With the rising of income, the consumption of Chinese residents is shifting from the "subsistence" type to the "well-off" type. First, the proportion of optional consumption has increased substantially. Comparing the structure of the total retail sales of social consumer goods in 2003 and 2019, it is found that the proportion of required consumption dropped from 31% in 2003 to 22% in 2019, and the proportion of optional consumption increased significantly, for example, car-related consumption increased from 25% in 2003 to 40% in 2019(table 1) . Second, the proportion of service consumption continued to increase, forming a two-wheel drive pattern of service consumption and commodity consumption. In 2019, service consumption accounted for 45.9 percent of China's per capita consumer spending, up 1.7 percentage points from the previous year.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Optional consumption, service consumption is more affected by the epidemic. When the impact of the epidemic, consumption will inevitably decrease, rice, grain and oil consumption will be relatively stable, and cars, tourism and other optional consumption will be more affected. In addition, service consumption is mostly non-essential and depends on face-to-face supply, which is more serious than commodity consumption. Judging from this, the impact of the epidemic on consumption will be greater than the SARS period.

Consumption will rebound strongly in the future

The short-term epidemic situation to each kind of consumption structural impact is obvious, the forecast consumption growth rate will drop greatly.

During its peak period (May) , the SARS epidemic caused consumption growth to drop by 5 percentage points to 4.3 per cent in the month. The impact of the outbreak on consumption is expected to be greater than during the SARS period. Consumption is expected to drop to around 3% in january-february 2020, and the recovery time of consumption growth depends on the control of the epidemic.

But the impact on consumption will be short-term and structural (table 2) .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
First, the impact of the epidemic on the consumption of essential goods is less than on the consumption of non-essential goods.

Second, the impact of epidemic situation on time-optional non-essential consumption is less than that on time-optional non-essential consumption. Take tourism consumption and office supplies consumption as an example, the tourism consumption demand delayed by the epidemic will be released after the end of the epidemic, so the impact of the epidemic on tourism consumption is relatively small; But people because of the epidemic reduced consumption of office supplies, it is more difficult to make up after the end of the epidemic, so this part of consumption lost.

Third, the impact of epidemic situation on the online alternative consumption is less than on the online alternative consumption. For example, it is difficult to substitute on-line for leisure and entertainment consumption such as theme park, and the loss of consumption is more, while it is easy to substitute on-line for consumption such as clothing, shoes and hats, and so on.

The recovery growth of all kinds of consumption growth rate in the future is expected. Some of the consumer demand that was suppressed during the outbreak has not disappeared but has only been postponed. Due to the need of epidemic prevention and control, the residents'consumption demand is greatly restrained by reducing their travel, which is expected to be released effectively after the end of the epidemic. Taking SARS as an example, after the epidemic subsided in July 2003, a large number of previously suppressed consumer demand was released, among which, clothing, shoes and hats, knitwear and textiles, sports and entertainment items, which decreased by a large margin in the consumption of retail products, cultural and office supplies are all back to pre-epidemic levels or even higher.

The government has taken multiple measures to bail out enterprises in the consumer sector. It is expected that the supply side will recover more quickly after the end of the epidemic, so that consumer demand can be better met. Since the outbreak of the epidemic, the central and local governments have taken various measures to ease the financial pressure on small and medium-sized enterprises (smes) , especially those in the consumer industries hit hard by the epidemic, and to help smes tide over the difficulties. For example, the Central Government's Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China meeting on February 12 made it clear that it would "improve the fiscal, taxation, financial and social security policies in support of msmes" . The China State Council executive meeting, held on February 11, called for "the establishment of special support mechanisms for enterprises to deal with the epidemic and ease the difficulties of enterprises, especially private and small and micro enterprises. ". The CBRC requires all banking and insurance institutions, for the wholesale and retail, accommodation and catering, logistics and transportation, cultural tourism and other industries that have been seriously affected by the epidemic, as well as those enterprises that have development prospects but are temporarily stranded, we will not blindly pump out, cut off or squelch loans, and encourage relevant enterprises to tide over difficulties by appropriately lowering loan interest rates, improving loan renewal policy arrangements, increasing credit loans and medium-and long-term loans. The implementation of various relief measures will better protect the strength of enterprises in the consumer sector. When the epidemic subsides, the supply side will recover more quickly and effectively meet the consumer demand rebound after the epidemic.

Consumption, including food and tourism, which has been hit hard by the outbreak, will rebound significantly once the epidemic is over. Judging from the consumption demand in recent years, eating out and traveling have become the daily life style of many people. In 2019, China's catering revenue reached 4,672.1 billion yuan, an increase of 9.4 percent over the previous year; the number of domestic tourists will exceed 6 billion, an increase of about 500 million over the previous year. The Spring Festival is usually a key time for people to release the demand for travel and dining out, while the 2020 Spring Festival will be closed at home due to the prevention and control of the epidemic, which will make travel and dining out consumption impossible, but further stimulated people's consumption desire. After the end of the epidemic, related consumer demand will show a retaliatory rebound. Food consumption, the end of the epidemic is expected to appear within 1-2 months of a small peak, and then turn to 9%-10% of the normal growth rate. In terms of tourism consumption, the "May Day" , "Dragon Boat Festival" and summer vacation in 2020 will be the key time to release the accumulated demand for tourism consumption, and a small peak in tourism is expected. After the "November" Golden Week, tourism consumption will return to the normal growth range.

"homestead economy" in China

Historically, outbreaks have had a negative impact on the economy, but they have also accelerated the escalation of related industries. The US financial crisis of 1928, for example, gave birth to supermarket chains, and the SARS epidemic of 2003 gave birth to online retail giants such as Alibaba. This epidemic is also "crisis" in Tibet "opportunity" , or into the evolution of the retail industry and Change "catalyst" to speed up the rise of new retail model, consumer retail to bring new opportunities.

First, the online-to-offline integration of retail mode (O2o mode) into the trend. In order to reduce the unnecessary contact of personnel and reduce the cost of supply and logistics, all the major stores and convenience stores introduced new models, such as self-pick-up reservation and no-touch delivery to home, with great success. SUNING vegetable market, for example, during the epidemic suning vegetable market single-store orders increased by 7-10 times. In the future, with the continuous development and maturity of online live broadcast and community sales, O2O retail model will become a new trend of entity retail industry.

Second, the "no contact" concept of unmanned retail process to speed up again. In recent years, China's unmanned retail business has developed rapidly, unmanned vending machines, unmanned convenience stores and unmanned supermarkets, etc. . However, compared with developed countries, China's unmanned retail also has a lot of room for development (table 3) . In this epidemic, the concept of "no contact" became popular, China's unmanned retail process again accelerated, hospitals and epidemic areas opened a large number of unmanned distribution and unmanned supermarkets. For example, Wuhan Huoshenshan Hospital No supermarket, some other hospitals with robot food delivery; Meituan first in Wuhan, Beijing two pilot operation of "Meituan Intelligent Buffet" . These unmanned distribution and unmanned retail practices not only help to accumulate technical experience, but also help to improve public acceptance of unmanned retail and speed up the process of unmanned retail popularization.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Third, fresh electric business ushered in the new air. Before the outbreak, most of the consumers who had the experience of online shopping did not have the habit of buying fresh food online, but under the pressure of the epidemic, the fresh e-commerce became the first choice for urban people to buy food. For example, Youxian daily has four times as many fresh online orders in the first five days of 2020 as in the same period last year, and sold 40 million pieces of food during the seven day Lunar New Year holiday, sales rose 215 per cent year on year. During the outbreak, the 14-day home quarantine period not only enhanced consumers'trust and recognition of fresh e-commerce, but also made consumers form the habit of purchasing fresh online, and the future development of fresh e-commerce can be expected.

It is suggested that commercial banks should strengthen the financial support for small and medium-sized enterprises, especially those in consumer industries, as well as the enterprises and personnel involved in epidemic prevention and control, so as to serve the overall situation of national epidemic prevention and control and the restoration of economic and social order. In the medium and long term, it is suggested to seize the opportunity brought by the reform of the consumer retail industry, which is brewing in the current epidemic crisis, and lay out in advance. At the same time, we should take multiple measures to strengthen risk prevention and firmly hold the bottom line of non-occurrence of systemic financial risks.

One is to increase the disaster-hit catering, tourism, transportation and other industries of financial support and flexibility. On the one hand, in the light of the actual capacity of small and medium-sized enterprises and the temporary difficulties caused by the epidemic, they will be helped to tide over the difficulties through measures such as increasing loan quotas, extending loan terms and lowering interest rates. On the other hand, depending on the specific circumstances of each enterprise, adhering to the principle of "special task" , actively take more innovative measures to tailor-made comprehensive financial services programs to help enterprises resume production and operation.

Second, to increase the production of epidemic prevention materials, people's livelihood and other related enterprises and epidemic prevention front-line personnel financial support. On the one hand, by increasing the amount of loans and providing special loans, we will increase the financial support for enterprises that produce epidemic-prevention materials such as medicines and medical equipment, as well as for enterprises that guarantee people's livelihood such as logistics, transportation and supermarkets, we will help it recover and expand its production capacity as soon as possible, and improve the supply of epidemic prevention materials and the livelihood of the people. On the other hand, we will strengthen financial protection for people involved in epidemic prevention, such as providing free anonymous insurance for medical and health care workers, civilian police and community workers who take part in frontline epidemic prevention work.

In the medium and long term, we should seize the opportunity of consumer upgrading and retail reform and lay out in advance.

First, we will accelerate the distribution of upgraded consumer sectors. Through establishing cooperation with leading enterprises in the field of upgraded consumption, we will actively distribute upgraded consumption areas such as tourism, medical care and health preservation, and launch more abundant consumer financial products, provide better financial support for residents to upgrade their consumption.

The second is to speed up the construction of online and offline scene channels, to create a new internet financial ecological platform. Following the trend of online and offline integration of retail consumption, we focus on APP as the main online scene platform, with payment and credit as the core function, and constantly enrich the offline consumption scene, and improve the financial function.

Third, strengthen cooperation and development with large-scale e-commerce enterprises. Actively establish long-term strategic partnership with leading e-commerce enterprises, and continue to expand the depth and breadth of cooperation, search for business models, credit mechanism and other breakthroughs.

Fourth, focus on financial technology, optimize consumer financial services experience. On the one hand, the use of Internet technology to break through the geographical constraints of the advantages of a deeper level into the segmentation of consumption scenarios, provide embedded comprehensive financial services, to achieve customer groups, channels, products and other multi-dimensional value discovery and creation. On the other hand, establish user experience monitoring system and feedback mechanism to obtain direct feedback from users, and continuously optimize customer financial service experience.

(Zhou Jingtong is a research fellow at the Bank of China Research Institute, and Ye is a postdoctoral fellow at the Bank of China Research Institute; Editor: Wang Yanchun)
